Multispecies SDM with Physiology

## setup
suppressPackageStartupMessages({
  library(dismo)
  library(GRaF)
  library(raster)
  library(ggplot2)
  library(ggmap)
  library(rgbif)
  library(dplyr)
})

The purpose here is to see if we can use priors imposed on a Gaussian Process functional family to inform species distribution models de novo. Much of this code is copied from files that also exist in this directory. First well load some of the physiology data.

Load Physiology

physiology = read.csv("../data/physiology/Sundayetal_thermallimits.csv")
print(nrow(physiology))

Weve got 300 species total with some sort of physiological information from the literature (see Sunday et al). Lets filter to just the ones that weve got both \(T_{min}\) and \(T_{max}\) for:

physiology_nona = physiology[!is.na(physiology$tmax) & !is.na(physiology$tmin),]
nrow(physiology_nona)
## [1] 131

Now weve got 131 species for which species physiology isnt an issue. Lets pick a species at random and extract the GBIF data for it.

spec = gsub("_", " ", sample_n(physiology_nona, 1)$species)
print(spec)
## [1] "Liolaemus cf elongatus"
occs = occ_data(scientificName = spec, limit = 10000)
occs = occs$data
print(paste(spec, "occurences:", nrow(occs)))
## [1] "Liolaemus cf elongatus occurences: 1202"

Get pseudoabsences with range buffers.

Heres a plot of all of these occurrences:

occs = occs %>% filter(!is.na(decimalLatitude) & !is.na(decimalLongitude))
coordinates(occs) = ~decimalLongitude + decimalLatitude
ggmap(get_map(location = bbox(occs))) + 
  geom_point(data=as.data.frame(occs), aes(x=decimalLongitude, y=decimalLatitude))
